05762nam a22009015i 9780674369603DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)889747956  a(OCoLC)987928663  a97806743696037 a10.4159/97806743696032doi  a(DE-B1597)460891  a(OCoLC)881430453  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a342.730782231 aPost, Robert C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCitizens Divided :bCampaign Finance Reform and the Constitution /cRobert C. Post.  aPilot project,eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Tanner Lectures on Human Values ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tI. The Lectures -- t1. First Lecture: A Short History of Representation and Discursive Democracy -- t2. Second Lecture: Campaign Finance Reform and the First Amendment -- tII. Commentary -- t3. Out-Posting Post -- t4. Legitimacy, Strict Scrutiny, and the Case Against the Supreme Court -- t5. Free Speech as the Citizen’s Right -- t6. Citizens Deflected: Electoral Integrity and Political Reform -- tIII. Response -- t7. Representative Democracy -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tCommentators -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Supreme Court's 5-4 decision in Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission, which struck down a federal prohibition on independent corporate campaign expenditures, is one of the most controversial opinions in recent memory. Defenders of the First Amendment greeted the ruling with enthusiasm, while advocates of electoral reform recoiled in disbelief. Robert Post offers a new constitutional theory that seeks to reconcile these sharply divided camps. Post interprets constitutional conflict over campaign finance reform as an argument between those who believe self-government requires democratic participation in the formation of public opinion and those who believe that self-government requires a functioning system of representation. The former emphasize the value of free speech, while the latter emphasize the integrity of the electoral process. Each position has deep roots in American constitutional history. Post argues that both positions aim to nurture self-government, which in contemporary life can flourish only if elections are structured to create public confidence that elected officials are attentive to public opinion. Post spells out the many implications of this simple but profound insight. Critiquing the First Amendment reasoning of the Court in Citizens United, he also shows that the Court did not clearly grasp the constitutional dimensions of corporate speech. Blending history, constitutional law, and political theory, Citizens Divided explains how a Supreme Court case of far-reaching consequence might have been decided differently, in a manner that would have preserved both First Amendment rights and electoral integrity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCampaign fundsxLaw and legislationxUnited States. 0aCampaign fundsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawxUnited States. 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aElection lawxUnited States. 0aElection lawzUnited States. 0aElectionsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aElectionszUnited States. 0aLaw reformxUnited States. 0aLaw reformzUnited States. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh1 aKarlan, Pamela S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLessig, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichelman, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4ht